- "Crungji?"

526
00:28:14,202 --> 00:28:17,172
In Korea, it is a popular item these days.

527
00:28:17,302 --> 00:28:20,742
We take a croissant, then we press it...

528
00:28:20,872 --> 00:28:22,771
- with some sugar on both sides.
- Press?

529
00:28:22,772 --> 00:28:23,781
Okay.

530
00:28:23,782 --> 00:28:27,211
Is the base a French croissant?

531
00:28:27,212 --> 00:28:28,812
- Yes, French croissant.
- Okay.

532
00:28:28,882 --> 00:28:30,151
- I'll have it.
- Yes, one.

533
00:28:30,152 --> 00:28:31,422
Do you want 1 to share or 2?

534
00:28:32,052 --> 00:28:34,552
- I want it too.
- Two? Okay. Perfect, thank you.

535
00:28:35,252 --> 00:28:36,321
- Croissant...
- Croissant...

536
00:28:36,322 --> 00:28:37,322
(Buzzing)

537
00:28:37,323 --> 00:28:41,262
I ordered one because I want to see how they changed our croissant.

538
00:28:41,432 --> 00:28:45,231
This is a diplomatic issue.

539
00:28:45,232 --> 00:28:47,101
If it tastes bad,

540
00:28:47,102 --> 00:28:48,702
I won't sit still.

541
00:28:51,572 --> 00:28:53,971
(They're at risk of a diplomatic crisis!)

542
00:28:53,972 --> 00:28:56,482
Yes. Please help me.

543
00:28:56,582 --> 00:28:57,681
Put one here.

544
00:28:57,682 --> 00:28:59,362
(Putting on new gloves with determination)

545
00:29:00,212 --> 00:29:01,252
Right?

546
00:29:05,752 --> 00:29:09,092
(The fate of the two nations are at stake.)

547
00:29:09,722 --> 00:29:13,092
(Baker King's crungji)

548
00:29:13,832 --> 00:29:18,262
(Carefully sticking in the Korean flag)

549
00:29:19,432 --> 00:29:22,702
(Will crungji be a diplomatic success?)

550
00:29:23,402 --> 00:29:27,712
(An unofficial Korean-French dessert is coming.)

551
00:29:27,912 --> 00:29:31,412
(Following)

552
00:29:31,512 --> 00:29:33,452
- Amazing.
- Let's go.

553
00:29:33,512 --> 00:29:34,612
Okay.

554
00:29:35,712 --> 00:29:36,881
(The crungji diplomat is on an offsite inspection.)

555
00:29:36,882 --> 00:29:39,352
(Nervous)

556
00:29:39,792 --> 00:29:42,751
Did the chef make the croissant?

557
00:29:42,752 --> 00:29:44,291
Actually, he made the croissant.

558
00:29:44,292 --> 00:29:45,791
You really smashed the croissant.

559
00:29:45,792 --> 00:29:46,792
This guy made the croissant.

560
00:29:46,792 --> 00:29:47,792
- This guy?
- Yes.

561
00:29:47,793 --> 00:29:49,661
- Did you use a machine?
- Yes.

562
00:29:49,662 --> 00:29:50,761
(I pressed it with my hands.)

563
00:29:50,762 --> 00:29:51,902
Amazing.

564
00:29:53,102 --> 00:29:55,831
(The friend who swore he wouldn't sit still returned.)

565
00:29:55,832 --> 00:29:57,301
- Thank you.
- He smashed the croissant.

566
00:29:57,302 --> 00:29:58,302
He's the bad guy.

567
00:29:58,303 --> 00:29:59,342
He's the smasher.

568
00:30:00,542 --> 00:30:01,612
Thank you.

569
00:30:01,872 --> 00:30:04,982
They really smashed the croissant.

570
00:30:06,452 --> 00:30:10,152
(How will the smashed croissant taste?)

571
00:30:10,982 --> 00:30:13,592
(Crispy)

572
00:30:14,852 --> 00:30:17,792
(Taking a cautious bite)

573
00:30:17,962 --> 00:30:20,191
I think it's burnt.

574
00:30:20,192 --> 00:30:21,461
(I've never had such a croissant.)

575
00:30:21,462 --> 00:30:22,531
You're right.

576
00:30:22,532 --> 00:30:23,732
(Laughing)

577
00:30:26,732 --> 00:30:28,032
I'm not sure about the taste.

578
00:30:28,802 --> 00:30:31,242
It is kind of chewy.

579
00:30:32,842 --> 00:30:35,412
They insulted the know-hows of the French.

580
00:30:35,872 --> 00:30:38,812
(Ultraconservatives of croissants)

581
00:30:39,882 --> 00:30:43,382
(But they're still trying it.)

582
00:30:44,452 --> 00:30:47,652
Really? All right.

583
00:30:48,222 --> 00:30:52,092
(The unofficial French diplomat is trying it too.)

584
00:31:06,542 --> 00:31:08,642
It's as hard as a sole.

585
00:31:10,342 --> 00:31:12,542
Try it.

586
00:31:14,712 --> 00:31:17,322
Does it taste like a croissant with ice cream?

587
00:31:19,322 --> 00:31:20,922
Actually, it's not so bad.

588
00:31:21,052 --> 00:31:22,291
Come on, it's just vanilla and croissant.

589
00:31:22,292 --> 00:31:24,161
Yes, that's true,

590
00:31:24,162 --> 00:31:27,231
but what can I do if I like it?

591
00:31:27,232 --> 00:31:29,732
(Switching to Progressive Croissant Party)

592
00:31:29,862 --> 00:31:32,702
(This friend is eating it with his hands.)

593
00:31:33,172 --> 00:31:37,642
(I'll eat it with my hands too.)

594
00:31:39,142 --> 00:31:40,271
(He wants to use his fork no matter what.)

595
00:31:40,272 --> 00:31:42,912
(Strange)

596
00:31:43,242 --> 00:31:45,081
(Though he uses the fork strangely, he eats well.)

597
00:31:45,082 --> 00:31:47,882
(Scraping the plate)

598
00:31:53,022 --> 00:31:56,562
(More crungji are ready to tackle the other tables.)

599
00:31:56,622 --> 00:31:58,161
(Eyes fixed on it)

600
00:31:58,162 --> 00:31:59,522
The dessert is coming.

601
00:31:59,832 --> 00:32:02,432
(The crungji stole his attention.)

602
00:32:02,562 --> 00:32:05,432
(Staring intently)

603
00:32:06,432 --> 00:32:09,431
(Eyes fixed on the dessert for the other table)

604
00:32:09,432 --> 00:32:10,941
Is that an escalope?

605
00:32:10,942 --> 00:32:12,772
No, it's a croissant.

606
00:32:13,042 --> 00:32:16,212
(They do look alike.)

607
00:32:16,842 --> 00:32:18,882
It's a flattened croissant.

608
00:32:20,252 --> 00:32:21,552
I've never tried it, though.

609
00:32:21,582 --> 00:32:22,712
Why not?

610
00:32:23,522 --> 00:32:25,882
Because it would ruin the true taste of a croissant.

611
00:32:27,052 --> 00:32:29,922
(They ordered a crungji.)

612
00:32:30,062 --> 00:32:34,262
(This couple is trying something new.)

613
00:32:35,062 --> 00:32:36,902
It's nice but shocking.

614
00:32:37,802 --> 00:32:41,172
(They're shocked by how crungji looks.)

615
00:32:41,572 --> 00:32:44,902
It was really nice to eat here. I enjoyed it.

616
00:32:46,102 --> 00:32:49,272
(Finishing on a satisfactory note with the dessert)

617
00:32:50,142 --> 00:32:51,641
The flags are really cute.

618
00:32:51,642 --> 00:32:52,781
- The flags?
- Yes.

619
00:32:52,782 --> 00:32:54,451
They were originally for cheese balls.

620
00:32:54,452 --> 00:32:55,811
It's very nice.

621
00:32:55,812 --> 00:32:56,998
(Thanks to that, Baker King is happy.)

622
00:32:57,022 --> 00:32:58,922
What is the reaction like for the crungji?

623
00:32:59,622 --> 00:33:00,652
Good.

624
00:33:01,292 --> 00:33:03,532
Have they tried it before? It's their first time, right?

625
00:33:03,662 --> 00:33:05,022
It's everyone's first time.

626
00:33:05,122 --> 00:33:09,861
They found it a bit strange to see a flat croissant,

627
00:33:09,862 --> 00:33:11,661
but they all enjoyed it.

628
00:33:11,662 --> 00:33:12,761
Everyone finished it.

629
00:33:12,762 --> 00:33:13,802
I'm glad.

630
00:33:14,802 --> 00:33:17,141
- Thank you. Good night.
- Thank you.

631
00:33:17,142 --> 00:33:18,142
Thank you.

632
00:33:18,372 --> 00:33:20,371
- Thank you.
- Yes.

633
00:33:20,372 --> 00:33:21,511
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

634
00:33:21,512 --> 00:33:22,741
- Thank you.
- Bye.

635
00:33:22,742 --> 00:33:23,982
(The customers are leaving.)

636
00:33:24,742 --> 00:33:28,752
(The diplomats are the last to leave.)

637
00:33:29,482 --> 00:33:32,582
(The kitchen is closed.)

638
00:33:32,782 --> 00:33:33,992
John, look at this.

639
00:33:34,692 --> 00:33:36,791
This alone makes us happy, doesn't it?

640
00:33:36,792 --> 00:33:38,291
- We have a lot.
- Amazing.

641
00:33:38,292 --> 00:33:39,591
(They have a big pile of receipts.)

642
00:33:39,592 --> 00:33:41,691
- We did well.
- Today was a complete success.

643
00:33:41,692 --> 00:33:43,208
(The leftover food is proportional to the receipts.)

644
00:33:43,232 --> 00:33:44,562
Today was a success.

645
00:33:46,132 --> 00:33:47,202
Good work.

646
00:33:47,272 --> 00:33:48,901
- Good work.
- Good job.

647
00:33:48,902 --> 00:33:51,183
(They had 100 bowls as the goal. How much did they make?)

648
00:33:51,742 --> 00:33:54,712
(A tiring day has ended.)

649
00:33:56,782 --> 00:34:00,612
(The dawn is breaking.)

650
00:34:02,782 --> 00:34:05,982
(And what does the morning mean to Chef Paik and his team?)

651
00:34:06,122 --> 00:34:07,221
Shall we?

652
00:34:07,222 --> 00:34:08,491
(It's time to check the sales again.)

653
00:34:08,492 --> 00:34:09,692
- Here we go.
- Okay.

654
00:34:10,092 --> 00:34:11,861
"Are you ready to conquer France,"

655
00:34:11,862 --> 00:34:13,022
"the culinary powerhouse?"

656
00:34:14,262 --> 00:34:15,762
Was it our sixth day?

657
00:34:16,392 --> 00:34:17,702
- Yes, 6th.
- Our 6th day.

658
00:34:18,732 --> 00:34:20,802
Here are the sales for our sixth day.

659
00:34:21,872 --> 00:34:25,642
(4 places are competing against Single Pan House.)

660
00:34:25,742 --> 00:34:28,041
(Day 6 sales of the 1 million dollar alley)

661
00:34:28,042 --> 00:34:30,041
(Restaurant L, Restaurant P, Burger Place P, Restaurant M, )

662
00:34:30,042 --> 00:34:34,611
(Single Pan House)

663
00:34:34,612 --> 00:34:35,651
What?

664
00:34:35,652 --> 00:34:37,252
Mondays are usually slow.

665
00:34:38,082 --> 00:34:41,051
(Restaurant P: Fritters and burgers)

666
00:34:41,052 --> 00:34:42,092
What?

667
00:34:43,422 --> 00:34:45,422
It's not that high overall.

668
00:34:46,092 --> 00:34:50,101
(Burger Place P: Handcrafted burgers)

669
00:34:50,102 --> 00:34:53,372
(You again?)

670
00:34:53,702 --> 00:34:54,872
- What?
- For real?

671
00:34:55,102 --> 00:34:57,001
- Burger for dinner?
- Why eat so many burgers?

672
00:34:57,002 --> 00:34:58,801
The burger place is open until late.

673
00:34:58,802 --> 00:34:59,901
Did customers order takeaways?

674
00:34:59,902 --> 00:35:01,541
- There are many takeaways.
- Yes.

675
00:35:01,542 --> 00:35:02,542
Takeaways?

676
00:35:02,543 --> 00:35:03,881
The place didn't have many customers.

677
00:35:03,882 --> 00:35:04,882
Exactly.

678
00:35:05,642 --> 00:35:07,281
(We're still jealous.)

679
00:35:07,282 --> 00:35:08,512
(Tapping)

680
00:35:09,352 --> 00:35:13,152
(Restaurant M: Italian cuisine)

681
00:35:13,492 --> 00:35:14,521
That's less than before.

682
00:35:14,522 --> 00:35:16,191
But 4,278 is still a lot.

683
00:35:16,192 --> 00:35:17,261
That's quite high.

684
00:35:17,262 --> 00:35:19,192
- What did they sell for lunch?
- Cheese.

685
00:35:20,032 --> 00:35:21,291
(Correct)

686
00:35:21,292 --> 00:35:22,991
- They must've had a get-together.
- It's high.

687
00:35:22,992 --> 00:35:24,131
(All that's left is Single Pan House!)

688
00:35:24,132 --> 00:35:26,362
How much do you predict, Chef Paik?

689
00:35:26,772 --> 00:35:27,832
I don't make predictions.

690
00:35:28,332 --> 00:35:30,841
I worked without thinking.

691
00:35:30,842 --> 00:35:32,041
(A bad feeling)

692
00:35:32,042 --> 00:35:33,802
How much, Jang Woo? How much do you predict?

693
00:35:35,042 --> 00:35:36,211
About 1,600.

694
00:35:36,212 --> 00:35:37,981
(Single Pan House)

695
00:35:37,982 --> 00:35:40,252
I'm sure we easily went over 2,000.

696
00:35:41,052 --> 00:35:42,152
Really?

697
00:35:42,852 --> 00:35:45,051
(What's Single Pan House's day 6 sales?)

698
00:35:45,052 --> 00:35:51,221
(Single Pan House)

699
00:35:51,222 --> 00:35:52,521
(1st: Burger Place P, 2nd: Restaurant M, )

700
00:35:52,522 --> 00:35:53,661
(3rd: Single Pan House, 4th: Restaurant P, )

701
00:35:53,662 --> 00:35:54,991
(5th: Restaurant L)

702
00:35:54,992 --> 00:35:56,231
(Day 6 sales: 2,894 euros)

703
00:35:56,232 --> 00:35:58,632
(About 4,600 dollars)

704
00:35:59,032 --> 00:36:00,171
(What?)

705
00:36:00,172 --> 00:36:02,001
- What?
- We're in third place?

706
00:36:02,002 --> 00:36:03,132
We beat the burger place.

707
00:36:04,302 --> 00:36:06,602
- Hold on.
- What happened?

708
00:36:06,812 --> 00:36:08,941
- What? That's impossible.
- Unbelievable.

709
00:36:08,942 --> 00:36:10,211
We beat the burger place.

710
00:36:10,212 --> 00:36:11,941
(Shocked)

711
00:36:11,942 --> 00:36:14,281
(Battling with the turnover rate)

712
00:36:14,282 --> 00:36:16,451
(Day 6 of business)

713
00:36:16,452 --> 00:36:17,581
One hundred is enough.

714
00:36:17,582 --> 00:36:19,851
(Single Pan House did its best...)

715
00:36:19,852 --> 00:36:21,952
(by selling 100 bowls as the goal.)

716
00:36:23,252 --> 00:36:26,362
(Bibimbap sold during the day)

717
00:36:26,792 --> 00:36:30,831
(Number of bibimbap sold)

718
00:36:30,832 --> 00:36:34,902
(Number of bibimbap sold)

719
00:36:36,502 --> 00:36:39,541
(The last customer left at 10:15pm.)

720
00:36:39,542 --> 00:36:40,542
Bye.

721
00:36:40,543 --> 00:36:43,941
(The final number of bibimbap sold)

722
00:36:43,942 --> 00:36:48,352
(113 bowls)

723
00:36:49,612 --> 00:36:50,681
- What?
- Gosh.

724
00:36:50,682 --> 00:36:51,822
That's...

725
00:36:52,352 --> 00:36:53,892
What? That's impossible.

726
00:36:54,052 --> 00:36:55,092
Unbelievable.

727
00:36:55,552 --> 00:36:56,961
- We sold a lot.
- We did.

728
00:36:56,962 --> 00:36:58,621
- More than expected.
- Near the end...

729
00:36:58,622 --> 00:37:00,831
We always came in 1st and 2nd,

730
00:37:00,832 --> 00:37:02,862
so such a result can be disappointing.

731
00:37:02,932 --> 00:37:04,202
But we're good.

732
00:37:04,862 --> 00:37:06,132
How much do we have left?

733
00:37:07,272 --> 00:37:10,572
(Progress to making 1 million dollars a year)

734
00:37:10,672 --> 00:37:12,901
(5-day total: 8,558 euros)

735
00:37:12,902 --> 00:37:14,711
(Progress to making 1 million dollars a year)

736
00:37:14,712 --> 00:37:18,281
(6-day total: 10,752 euros)

737
00:37:18,282 --> 00:37:22,152
(About 2,069 euros or 3,300 dollars left until 1 million dollars)

738
00:37:22,382 --> 00:37:23,521
Three thousand dollars.

739
00:37:23,522 --> 00:37:25,182
We only need to sell 2,000 euros more.

740
00:37:26,382 --> 00:37:30,492
(If it's 2,000 euros in the remaining 2 days, )

741
00:37:31,162 --> 00:37:33,362
(we might make it in one day.)

742
00:37:33,792 --> 00:37:35,672
Why don't we open for lunch and dinner today...

743
00:37:36,732 --> 00:37:38,231
and rest tomorrow?

744
00:37:38,232 --> 00:37:39,262
(Why not rest tomorrow?)

745
00:37:39,662 --> 00:37:41,131
Reach that, and we won't need to open.

746
00:37:41,132 --> 00:37:42,502
But over 3,000 dollars.

747
00:37:42,972 --> 00:37:44,071
We can quit right away.

748
00:37:44,072 --> 00:37:46,271
I'm taking my mic off the minute we're done.

749
00:37:46,272 --> 00:37:47,512
(Should we finish it today?)

750
00:37:48,142 --> 00:37:50,541
(3,300 dollars in a single day?)

751
00:37:50,542 --> 00:37:53,111
It'll be easy peasy.

752
00:37:53,112 --> 00:37:55,452
(It'll be easy peasy.)

753
00:37:55,852 --> 00:37:57,151
Here's a possibility.

754
00:37:57,152 --> 00:38:01,091
Say that business goes well today and we reach 2,000 euros.

755
00:38:01,092 --> 00:38:02,421
We're not opening on the last day.

756
00:38:02,422 --> 00:38:04,302
(Reaching 1 million dollars early is possible.)

757
00:38:04,662 --> 00:38:06,761
I had this feeling we had to do it.

758
00:38:06,762 --> 00:38:08,191
(What's the strategy for reaching it today?)

759
00:38:08,192 --> 00:38:09,891
(The strategy to close business today)

760
00:38:09,892 --> 00:38:11,461
(Offer all superstar menus.)

761
00:38:11,462 --> 00:38:13,231
It was a big hit, so we should do it again.

762
00:38:13,232 --> 00:38:16,201
It's beyond imagination for a French person...

763
00:38:16,202 --> 00:38:18,942
to practice Korean to say how delicious it is.

764
00:38:19,102 --> 00:38:20,102
I'm serious.

765
00:38:21,672 --> 00:38:23,411
(Here are the superstars...)

766
00:38:23,412 --> 00:38:25,681
(that'll help Single Pan House reach...)

767
00:38:25,682 --> 00:38:29,681
(1 million dollars in annual sales.)

768
00:38:29,682 --> 00:38:31,621
(The superstar of business day 2)

769
00:38:31,622 --> 00:38:33,621
("This is amazing." From Table 7)

770
00:38:33,622 --> 00:38:34,991
(Gochujang bulgogi)

771
00:38:34,992 --> 00:38:36,152
Let's make it spicy.

772
00:38:38,222 --> 00:38:41,691
(Upgraded to the main single pan menu)

773
00:38:41,692 --> 00:38:45,701
(Today's single pan: Spicy stir-fried squid and pork)

774
00:38:45,702 --> 00:38:46,731
(The superstar of business day 6)

775
00:38:46,732 --> 00:38:49,572
(And the 3 superstars of yesterday's sales)

776
00:38:50,642 --> 00:38:52,101
("Incredible." From Table 9)

777
00:38:52,102 --> 00:38:53,671
("The beef tartare alone would be nice too." From Table 16)

778
00:38:53,672 --> 00:38:55,011
(Korean meatballs, the most ordered)

779
00:38:55,012 --> 00:38:56,311
(Beef tartare, the most satisfying topping)

780
00:38:56,312 --> 00:38:57,611
(Crungji, the biggest culture shock)

781
00:38:57,612 --> 00:38:59,581
I think pushing ahead is a good idea.

782
00:38:59,582 --> 00:39:01,551
(The plan is to battle with the popular menus.)

783
00:39:01,552 --> 00:39:03,681
Let's open at 6:30pm.

784
00:39:03,682 --> 00:39:05,452
Or we could open at 6pm, right?

785
00:39:05,652 --> 00:39:07,152
- Let's go.
- Okay.

786
00:39:07,752 --> 00:39:09,921
(It could be the last day of business.)

787
00:39:09,922 --> 00:39:10,991
We might reach over one million dollars...

788
00:39:10,992 --> 00:39:12,591
and be done today.

789
00:39:12,592 --> 00:39:15,992
(Will they reach the final goal with today's business?)

790
00:39:16,362 --> 00:39:17,801
(3:30pm)

791
00:39:17,802 --> 00:39:18,961
(Everyone is at work.)

792
00:39:18,962 --> 00:39:20,472
What nice weather.

793
00:39:22,772 --> 00:39:24,041
I'd love to dine over there.

794
00:39:24,042 --> 00:39:25,441
(The restaurant next door)

795
00:39:25,442 --> 00:39:26,642
